I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation able to create links with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We came of age during a media golden age, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We dove directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without a reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundations of our lives.
That's why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the series every Thursday.
It was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where all 12 episodes are available at once and everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specified closed spaces.
consciously we were dying to connect with the universal community surrounding all of this
that's why so many of us obsessively watch series like The Office or movies like Starman, full of short references, like memes.
we repeated these references, knowing that most people knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
there's too much to see and no way to rationalize it all... will we escape hyper-saturation?
we get caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to end up realizing the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
we're forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
we enter parasocial relationships with more awareness.
We understand that it's hard to reach positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
Due to a lack of collective awareness about media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us stay critical.
Some of us continue to place people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall from it.
We are in a turbulent period, and I'm eager to know where it will take us.
